    <h1 class="h1">LANGUAGE & CULTURE</h1>

    <h2>Discover the Essence of Egypt’s Identity</h2><br />

    <p>
        Egypt’s culture is a fascinating blend of ancient traditions and modern influences. The country’s heritage spans
        thousands of years, with its language, art, and customs deeply rooted in the time of the Pharaohs. Over centuries,
        Egypt has embraced the diversity brought by various civilizations while preserving its distinct character.
    </p>

    <p>
        The official language of Egypt is Arabic, and the local dialect—known as Egyptian Arabic—is widely understood across
        the Arab world due to Egypt’s influential media and film industry. English and French are also commonly spoken,
        especially in major cities and tourist areas, making communication easy for international visitors.
    </p>

    <p>
        Egyptian culture places great emphasis on hospitality, family values, and community. Visitors often notice the warm
        greetings, generosity, and friendliness of Egyptians, who take pride in sharing their culture, food, and stories.
        The country’s art scene is rich and diverse, encompassing music, cinema, literature, and dance.
    </p>

    <p>
        Traditional music, featuring instruments like the oud and tabla, is often heard during celebrations, while modern
        Egyptian pop continues to thrive regionally. Festivals such as Ramadan, Eid, and Coptic Christmas showcase Egypt’s
        cultural harmony, as people from different backgrounds celebrate together with joy and unity.
    </p>

    <p>
        From the timeless architecture of Islamic Cairo and the colorful Nubian villages of Aswan to the vibrant bazaars and
        the aroma of Egyptian coffee, every corner of the country tells a story of resilience, creativity, and spirit.
    </p><br />

    <h1 style="font-size:20px">DISCOVER</h1>
    <hi style="font-size:30px; font-weight:900;">Egyptian festivals and traditions</hi><br />
    <!-- Ramadan Card -->
    <div class="culture-card" style="background-color:#FFF8E5;">
        <img src="@Url.Content("~/images/About Egypt/5.jpg")" alt="Ramadan in Egypt">
        <div class="card-content">
            <h3>Ramadan – A Month of Faith, Family, and Festivity</h3>
            <p>
                Ramadan is the holy month of fasting celebrated by Muslims around the world, and in Egypt, it holds a truly special spirit. From sunrise to sunset, people fast as an act of devotion and self-reflection, breaking their fast each evening with Iftar, a joyful meal shared with family, friends, and neighbors.
                As the sun sets, Egyptian streets come alive with the warm glow of colorful lanterns (Fanous Ramadan) hanging from balconies and across alleyways, filling cities and villages alike with a magical atmosphere. Cafés and restaurants remain open late into the night, offering traditional sweets like Qatayef and Konafa, while the sound of laughter, music, and prayer fills the air.
                Throughout the month, Egyptians also embrace the spirit of generosity and community, with many people preparing meals for the poor and gathering together for nightly prayers known as Taraweeh. The sense of unity, joy, and spirituality during Ramadan transforms every corner of Egypt into a celebration of faith, love, and togetherness.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div><br />

    <h2>Food, Drink, & Entertainment</h2><br />

    <p>
        Egyptians love to talk, eat, and stay up late together. If you are looking for a travel experience that will enrich
        your life with genuine human connections and laughter, Egypt is the place to go! Perhaps owing to Egypt’s young population,
        with around 60% of Egyptians under 30, it is common to find Egyptians staying up late enjoying conversation or the latest football
        match over a shared meal or several rounds of tea. In Egypt, you will experience genuine hospitality and make lifelong friendships fast,
        usually revolving around a memorable meal or two...or maybe even three!
    </p>

    <p>
        Egyptian cuisine will most certainly not disappoint. Egyptian cuisine has plenty of vegan and pescatarian recipes that have been tried,
        tested, and developed through the ages, but an innovative culinary scene means you can go on food tours to sample a variety of tempting
        dishes in diverse settings, both traditional and upscale. Most hotels serve international cuisine alongside Egyptian dishes. Present-day
        Egypt is also known for being the cultural hub of the Arab world with a vast production of art, music, film, and a lively visual and performative
        arts scene—so after your meal, make sure to look up the current cultural events happening near you!
    </p>

