    <!-- Foul Card -->
    <div class="culture-card" style="background-color:#FFF8E5;">
        <img src="@Url.Content("~/images/About Egypt/6.jpg")" alt="Foul in Egypt">
        <div class="card-content">
            <h3>Foul – Egypt’s Beloved Breakfast Tradition</h3>
            <p>
                Foul, or fava beans, is the most iconic breakfast dish in Egypt and a cherished part of the country’s culinary heritage. These buttery, slow-cooked beans are simmered for hours with flavorful spices such as cumin, garlic, and lemon juice, creating a hearty and comforting meal that fuels millions of Egyptians every morning.
                It is traditionally served with baladi bread — a warm, fluffy Egyptian flatbread — and often topped with olive oil, tahini, chopped tomatoes, onions, or boiled eggs, depending on taste.
                From street vendors in Cairo’s bustling neighborhoods to family kitchens and local cafés, Foul represents the heart of Egyptian cuisine — simple, nourishing, and full of flavor. Whether enjoyed quickly before work or shared leisurely with friends, it perfectly reflects Egypt’s warm hospitality and everyday spirit.
            </p>
